# Route Tracker - GPS Data Receiver
A Node.js web application that receives GPS data from the Overlander iPhone app and displays route tracking in real-time.

## Architecture
- **Backend**: Node.js/Express API server receives GPS data via HTTP POST
- **Frontend**: Interactive web interface displays received routes on maps
- **Data Source**: iPhone Overlander app sends GPS coordinates to the server
- **Authentication**: Access tokens for secure data transmission
- **Storage**: Local JSON file storage for routes, devices, and tokens

## Features
- Receive real-time GPS data from Overlander iPhone app via HTTP API
- Display route tracking on interactive maps using Leaflet/OpenStreetMap  
- Support multiple data formats: all data, latest points, OwnTracks compatible
- Device management with unique device IDs for multiple iPhones
- User authentication with access tokens for secure data transmission
- Route history and statistics (distance, speed, elevation, duration)
- Export route data in multiple formats (GPX, KML, JSON, CSV)
- Real-time route visualization with start/end markers
- Auto-refresh capabilities for live tracking updates
- Responsive design for mobile and desktop use
- Data persistence with local file storage
- Notifications for route updates and system status
- Route sharing and social features
- Comprehensive API for route and device management

## Configuration
1. Set API token (default: 'default-token-123')
2. Configure Overlander iPhone app endpoint: http://server:6050/api/gps
3. Set device ID for tracking multiple devices
4. Choose data format (all/latest/owntracks)
5. Start GPS tracking in Overlander app

## API Endpoints
- POST /api/gps - Receive GPS data from iPhone (requires token)
- GET /api/devices/{deviceId} - Get device information
- GET /api/routes/{routeId} - Get specific route data
- GET /api/devices/{deviceId}/routes - List routes for device
- POST /api/devices/{deviceId}/stop-route - Stop active route
- POST /api/admin/tokens - Generate new access tokens (admin)

## Data Format Support
- Standard GPS: lat, lng, alt, speed, timestamp
- OwnTracks format: _type, lat, lon, tst, vel, acc, batt
- Device metadata: deviceId, routeName, accuracy
- Bulk upload: array of GPS points

## Installation
1. Clone the repository
2. Build Docker container with Node.js backend  
3. Start with docker-compose (port 6050)
4. Configure iPhone Overlander app with server endpoint

## Usage
1. Open web interface at http://server:6050
2. Set API token and device ID
3. Configure iPhone Overlander app with endpoint details
4. Start GPS tracking on iPhone
5. View real-time routes and statistics in web interface
6. Export route data as needed

## iPhone Overlander App Configuration
- Endpoint URL: http://your-server:6050/api/gps
- Access Token: default-token-123 (or custom token)
- Device ID: default-device (or custom ID)  
- HTTP Method: POST
- Content-Type: application/json
- Data Format: all, latest, or owntracks

The system transforms the Route Tracker from a browser-based GPS collector into a server-based GPS data receiver that works with the professional Overlander iPhone application for route tracking and location data management.